S3 policies 
=================
While AWS provides managed policies like AmazonS3FullAccess, these are often too broad for production environments 
because they grant permission to every S3 bucket in your account. Avoid these unless you are in 
a sandbox or development environment.

. Recommended Strategy for S3 Permissions
Instead of one massive policy, break it down by the type of work the user performs:

For Read-Only Users: Allow only s3:Get* and s3:List* actions on specific buckets.

For Developers/Managers: Allow s3:PutObject, s3:DeleteObject, and s3:ListBucket on specific bucket paths (prefixes) rather than the entire bucket.

For Console Users: If the user needs to use the AWS Management Console, they must have these additional permissions, or they will see "Access Denied" errors even if they have permission to access the data:

s3:ListAllMyBuckets

s3:GetBucketLocation

EC2 - Instance 
=====================

Recommended Production Approach (Least Privilege)
Granting AmazonEC2FullAccess gives a user control over every EC2 resource in the entire AWS account. 
In a real-world enterprise environment, standard practice dictates building a Customer Managed Policy tailored to the user's specific workflow.

          "ec2:StartInstances",
          "ec2:StopInstances",
          "ec2:RebootInstances"
          ec2:RunInstances  
This custom policy allows a user to monitor EC2 instances and perform basic lifecycle tasks (start/stop/reboot) without allowing them to delete the infrastructure or modify networking/security configurations.

However, launching an EC2 instance is complex because it often requires permissions for associated resources (like subnets, security groups, AMIs, and key pairs). 
Additionally, if you want to attach an IAM role to that instance, you must explicitly grant the iam:PassRole permission.

